---XPath--------
How many ways we can write xpath 
1.Absolute XPath
Starts from the root node (html) and goes till the target element.
/html/body/div/div[2]/input

2.Relative XPath
//input[@id='username']
✅ Recommended ✅ (Short & flexible)

3.XPath by Attribute
Locate element using attributes like id, name, class, type, etc.

//input[@name='email']

4.XPath by Text
Locate element using visible text.
//button[text()='Login']

5.Contains() Function

When attribute value is dynamic or partial.
Example:
xpath
//input[contains(@id, 'user')]

6.Starts-with() Function
Matches elements whose attribute starts with a certain value.
Example:
xpath
//input[starts-with(@id, 'login')]

7.XPath with AND/OR Conditions
Example:
xpath
//input[@type='text' and @name='email']

8.XPath using Parent-Child Relationship

//div[@class='form-group']/input

9.XPath using Following-Sibling
Example:
xpath
//label[text()='Email']/following-sibling::input

10.XPath using Ancestor & Descendant
//div[@class='container']//input[@id='email']
-----------                                ---------------------------------------------------




<input type="password" placeholder="Password" name="inputPassword" value="">
//input[@placeholder='Password'] 
//input[@type='password']
//input[@name='inputPassword']


